  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Syria: Fighting impunity and bringing justice for victims of war crimes and crimes against humanity</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Serious violations of international humanitarian law, including war crimes, and gross human rights abuses have been committed in Syria since 2011. Civilians have suffered under deadly indiscriminate and direct bombing attacks by government and allied forces. Tens of thousands of people, including peaceful activists, humanitarian workers, lawyers and journalists, are subjected to arbitrary arrest, enforced disappearance and torture or other ill-treatment. Access to humanitarian and medical aid to civilians living in government-controlled areas continues to be restricted. Simultaneously, armed groups also continue committing human rights abuses against civilians.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Universal jurisdiction is found to be an effective instrument for war crimes accountability in Syria since many perpetrators have left Syria and now live in countries which recognize Universal Jurisdiction (UJ). High quality documentation to build files is an important tool to make strong war crime cases. In 2020, AINL/HURICAP supported a Syrian organization with the documentation of witness testimonies and in its lobby and advocacy efforts for UJ and war crimes accountability in a number of European countries.</narrative>
  </description>
